P I L A T E S üíôR e f o r m e r 

Here are a few ‚Äúclassical Pilates‚Äù exercises designed by Joseph Pilates for the Reformer. 

During World War I, Pilates, who was living in England, was interned as a German "enemy alien". He used this time to develop his fitness program, which he later called "Contrology," focusing on mind-body connection and core strength. 

While in the internment camp, Pilates began teaching his fitness methods to fellow internees, and later, he worked as an orderly in a hospital on the Isle of Man, where he developed his apparatus by attaching bed springs to hospital beds to help rehabilitate patients unable to walk. 

The springs he used to help patients move and strengthen their muscles while bedridden became the inspiration for the iconic Pilates Reformer. 

After the war, Pilates returned to Germany and continued to study fitness and movement, eventually collaborating with experts in dance and physical exercise. He later emigrated to the United States, where he and his wife Clara opened a studio in New York City, where he worked with dancers and athletes. 

Today, Pilates is more popular than ever because it helps with everything. It‚Äôs one of the best workouts for your mind and body. Make sure you work with a certified Pilates teacher who has experience. 

üî∏First Video: 
Footwork-‚Äúrunning or prancing‚Äù. I like to do a set with the pelvis neutral & another set with the pelvis lifted a few inches off the mat. The footwork exercises were meant to activate all the important muscles in our feet similar to acupressure. The feet are responsible for three quarters of our body & help with balance. 

üî∏Second Video:
‚ÄúThe Shoulder Bridge‚Äù which is a great way to work your glutes and back while stretching the front of your hips and shoulders. Adding the magic circle and light dumbbells makes it even tougher. 

üî∏Third Video:
‚ÄúFeet in Straps‚Äù-Leg Circles are a favorite for most Pilates lovers because it massages our hips and feels amazing. 

üî∏4th Video
‚ÄúThe Shoulder Bridge‚Äù w heels together toes apart.

don‚Äôt be a major looser and learn some history about how the core principles and ethos of pilates is inclusivity. joseph pilates created the pilates exercise to rehabilitate fallen soldiers during World War I and thus started using hospital beds and their springs to create exercises for injured, sick, and disabled soldiers. which later laid the foundation for the pilates equipment you see today. fun fact: joseph pilates was inspired by eastern ideas about health and physical fitness such as yoga, tai chi, and zen meditation. he also was inspired by the stretches of cats üêà (how cute!). therefor pilates is a principle and practice that anyone can do, including the big girls. that‚Äôs all for my ted talk.

After nearly 450 hours of formal Pilates training (almost three years of classes, three days a week - two reformer and one mat), plus daily 5‚Äì15 minute home practice and a dozen 1:1 sessions after having Dean to heal my diastasis, I am officially a certified mat Pilates instructor! ‚ú®
-
I‚Äôve completely fallen in love with the intentionality and flow of Pilates. It‚Äôs transformed not only my training but also my body: my strength in weightlifting has increased, my posture has improved (feet, ankles, glute balance, even scoliosis), and my diastasis has fully closed. My core has never looked better - I always joke that I have no business having an 8-pack after two kids just 19 months apart, but I credit it all to Pilates.
-
Pilates has also been a game changer for my pelvic floor strength and mind‚Äìmuscle connection, which has carried over into everything - from better glute development, to improved core definition, to more confidence and yes, even incredible sex.
-
I‚Äôll be sharing many of my favorite flows here, and they‚Äôll also be part of my next challenge (starting October 13!). I can‚Äôt wait to bring these workouts to you in a more structured way. I know not everyone has access to in-person classes, so my hope is to help you experience the same love and benefits of Pilates that I have. üôèüèº

owner_name: Latest AI Tools | AI News | Technology Trends
caption:
AirPods Pro 3 introduces a set of breakthrough features, including real-time live translation, new fitness sensors, re-engineered sound hardware, much longer battery life, and refined comfort and accessibility options.

Live Translation and Multilingual Communication
Live Translation allows seamless, real-time conversations across languages using on-device Apple Intelligence.

Users can trigger translation mode with a gesture on the AirPods, automatically lowering background noise, then hear translated speech directly in their ears.

If both participants wear compatible AirPods, each hears translations in their own language; if only one does, live transcriptions appear on the paired iPhone for the other person.

At launch, languages include English, French, German, Portuguese (Brazil), and Spanish (Spain), with Italian, Japanese, Korean, and Chinese (simplified) coming later in 2025.

The USDA announced the termination of the annual Household Food Security Report, critical data on hunger in the U.S. Without this report, insight into the scope and severity of food insecurity will be lost. Refusing to collect the data, does not make the hunger crisis go away.

I‚Äôm leading a team at @hhsgov, along with @edsecmcmahon, targeting the woeful lack of nutrition education in medicine. We can reverse the chronic disease epidemic simply by changing our diets and lifestyles, but to do that, we need nutrition to be a basic part of every doctor‚Äôs training.
transcript: Hey everybody, I'm Robert F. Kennedy Jr., your HHS Secretary. Today, the Trump administration is demanding bold reform in our medical education system. I'm leading a team at HHS with the support of Secretary McMann at the Department of Education that targets a situation that everyone has long recognized as wrong, but no one has yet had the gumption to fix. It's the woeful lack of nutrition education in medicine. Poor diet drives America's chronic disease crisis, fueling seven of our ten deadliest conditions. Each year it claims an estimated one million American lives through diet-related illnesses. Meanwhile, we pour more than $4 trillion annually into treating these preventable diseases, and we continue to graduate physicians unprepared to confront their root cause. The good news is that diet not only causes these conditions, it can also prevent and reverse them. But for too long we've instead analyzed the chronic disease crisis, commissioned studies, and pontificated about the importance of nutrition without taking any meaningful action. Recent data reveals a critical disconnect. Although all medical schools claim to include nutrition in their curricula, most medical students report receiving no formal nutrition education throughout their entire training. This leads to a troubling reality. Most medical students recognize nutrition as necessary. Nearly all medical residents are asked to counsel patients about nutrition, but fewer than a quarter of practicing physicians feel adequately prepared to provide nutrition advice. We can reverse the chronic disease epidemic simply by changing our diets and lifestyles, but to do that, we need nutrition to be a basic part of every doctor's training. We'll start by embedding nutrition directly into college pre-med programs and testing it on the MCAT. Every future physician should master the language of prevention before they even touch a stethoscope. Under President Trump's leadership, we are going to systematically transform nutrition education throughout American medicine, from more than 200 of America's medical schools, 13,000 residency and fellowship programs, and ultimately each of the nation's 1.1 million practicing physicians. In the future, doctors won't just prescribe drugs, they'll be able to prescribe diets as well, confidently screening for diet-related diseases and collaborating with nutrition experts to recommend food-based solutions. Our reforms will save our country hundreds of billions of dollars and prevent millions of debilitating chronic diseases. This is an approach that is both radical and common sense. We're going to reconnect medicine with its roots. Hippocrates, the father of medicine, said, "Let food be thy medicine, and medicine be thy food." His advice remains true today, and we're bringing back food to its proper place in medicine. Produced by the US Department of Health and Human Services.

caption:
This week @usdagov proposed common-sense changes to more than double the healthy eating opportunities for our most vulnerable populations by strengthening the stocking requirements for retailers participating in the Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP). 

We‚Äôre seeking to raise the bar for stocking by: 
¬†
‚ñ™Ô∏èIncreasing variety requirements to seven per staple food category, more than DOUBLING the food choices required
‚ñ™Ô∏èClosing loopholes that allow certain snack foods to count as staple foods
‚ñ™Ô∏èSimplifying food classification, making standards easier for retailers to understand and @USDA_FNS to enforce
¬†
These changes will reorient SNAP towards better nutrition and emphasizing whole, healthy food for program participants. 

With the help of Dr. @RealBenCarson, who was officially sworn in this week as the USDA National Nutrition Advisor, we are delivering on @POTUS‚Äôs promise to turn the tide on chronic disease and MAKE AMERICA HEALTHY AGAIN! ü•ó
‚ÄúWe are going to have dietary guidelines that are based on science, not based on medical dogma.‚Äù ‚Äî @fda Commissioner Makary
Today, we released the Make Our Children Healthy Again strategy‚Äîthe most significant reform of food and healthcare policy in modern history.

The U.S. feed industry is a $250 billion powerhouse, fueling agriculture and the economy. With over 80,000 jobs across the U.S., it‚Äôs more than feed ‚Äî it‚Äôs a force driving innovation, nutrition and global leadership. #AFIA #FeedIndustry #MadeInAmerica
transcript: The American Feed Industry Association and its members are committed to meeting the world's growing demand for meats, milk, eggs, and seafood. With over 5,600 manufacturing facilities and a dedicated workforce of over 80,000 across the country, the animal food industry is a quarter trillion dollar a year powerhouse. It plays an essential role in the US economy and global food chain. Visit afia.org to learn how to support global food security and health.

caption:
The U.S. food environment, healthcare system, and social determinants of health disproportionately harm low-income populations.

As a result, health outcomes like obesity, chronic disease, and life expectancy show staggering disparities. Men in the highest income groups live 15 years longer than those in the lowest, and for women, the gap is 10 years (PMID: 27063997). 

Improving the health of Americans means focusing on those struggling the most. It means policies that make nutritious food accessible‚Äînot $48 olive oil, but produce that millions of Americans in food deserts lack access to. Nearly 14% of U.S. households, including 1 in 5 children, face food insecurity, where they can‚Äôt consistently get the food they need to meet basic nutritional needs.

It means expanding healthcare access, funding nutrition programs, and addressing economic stability and other social determinants of health‚Äîevidence-based solutions that benefit everyone, not just the wealthy.

Any movement claiming to ‚Äúmake America healthy‚Äù while ignoring these systemic issues isn‚Äôt genuine. And when that movement is led by wellness influencers profiting from expensive supplements, detoxes, and cold plunge pools‚Äîrather than public health experts - it‚Äôs even less genuine.

Make the move to reduce the added sugars in your diet!

Reducing intake of added sugars in our diets is the focus of the 2020-2025 Dietary Guidelines for Americans. A big reason for this focus is based on the finding that youth and adults in the United States consume twice the recommended daily amount of added sugars in their beverages alone.

Beverages such as sodas, some juices, energy drinks, sports drinks, and flavored water are a large source of added sugars. You'll also find added sugars in your flavored dairy products, baked goods, prepared sauces and dressings, and in some canned fruits.

It is recommended that we limit added sugars to 10% or less of our caloric intake per day, this is 50g based on a 2000-calorie per day diet. You can identify the amount of added sugar your food and beverages contain by referencing the nutrition facts label. As of 2021, these labels are required to identify added sugars in a product, separate from total sugars.

Here are a few tips to help you reduce the added sugar in your diet!
1. Move to more water - Cut one sugary drink out of your day and swap it for water! Need flavor? Add pureed fruit to make your water more tasty.
2. Read nutrition labels - Look at added sugars in the foods you eat and search for alternatives with less added sugars in them (i.e. no-sugar added barbecue sauce).
3. Replace sugar when baking - Use applesauce, banana, or sweet potatoes in place of sugar.
4. Make sauces and dressings from scratch - barbecue sauce, salad dressings, pasta/pizza sauce, and others can be made at home with less added sugar.

Increase your awareness of the foods and beverages you consume that contain added sugars and find one way to reduce the sugars in your diet this week.

The amount of sodium in the typical American diet definitely reaches these excessive levels. The average American eats about 3,400 milligrams (mg) of sodium a day‚Äîclose to 150 percent more than the daily limit recommended to avoid disease risk, 2,300 mg. Restaurant foods are a particularly concerning source of sodium for American consumers. Restaurant dishes contribute on average 31 percent of daily sodium consumption among adults and 26 percent among children.

We recently conducted a study that looked at the sodium content of menu items from the top 91 highest-grossing US restaurant chains, and found that many menu items at these large chains exceeded the daily recommended sodium value for US adults. This research also found excessive levels of salt hiding in unexpected menu items, like soups and salads that consumers might otherwise think are healthy, as well as sweet foods like desserts. Not ideal!

Almost 60 percent of the calories that adults in America eat are from ultra-processed foods. They are what scientists call hyper-palatable: irresistible, easy to overeat, and capable of hijacking the brain‚Äôs reward system and provoking powerful cravings.

Yet in dozens of large studies, scientists have found that ultra-processed foods are linked to higher rates of obesity, heart disease, hypertension, type 2 diabetes and colon cancer. A recent study of more than 22,000 people found that people who ate a lot of ultra-processed foods had a 19 percent higher likelihood of early death and a 32 percent higher risk of dying from heart disease compared with people who ate few ultra-processed foods.

Diet is the leading behavioural risk factor for death and chronic disease globally, and is the second such risk factor (after tobacco use) in older adults in the US. Understanding the relationship between diet and healthy ageing is important with ageing global populations. However, how dietary choices made during mid-life affect health in later years remains unclear. 

In a comprehensive analysis spanning three decades, Marta Guasch-Ferr√©, Anne-Julie Tessier, Frank B. Hu and colleagues identified specific dietary patterns that influence the likelihood of achieving healthy ageing, which includes maintaining cognitive, physical, and mental health beyond 70 years of age.

Eating a diet high in specific types of nutrients ‚Äî including fruits, vegetables, whole grains, unsaturated fats, nuts, legumes, and low-fat dairy products ‚Äî is associated with improved physical and mental health in older age. Meanwhile, greater intake of trans fats, sodium, sugary beverages, and red and/or processed meats was associated with poorer health in older age. 

The findings, based on an analysis of over 100,000 people in the US found that only 9.3% experienced healthy ageing and may help people improve their chances of living longer and healthier lives.

You can read the open access article published in Nature Medicine at the link in our bio.

Walking across America changed my body and it‚Äôs time to fix it

#walkacrossamerica #fitness
transcript:
Seven months ago, I walked 3,600 miles across America. And somehow, I'm still out of shape. You would think that after six months of walking, I would come home looking like Iron Man. But my body is basically only good for walking. I lost all my explosiveness, my upper-body strength vanished, and I dropped almost 20 pounds. Honestly, I am the weakest I have ever been in a lot of areas. But now I'm back home, three weeks in, and I've had to rebuild from scratch.

My numbers are still low, but I've made progress. In just two weeks, I've already put on 10 pounds. And I've even started to get a little bit of my hops back. But the grind doesn't stop. This is just the start.

What‚Äôs your favourite exercise? ü§î

Today‚Äôs clip comes from the latest podcast roundtable of @peterattiamd. My first mentor, Michael Boyle, along with the other guests, speaks to the lack of participation in resistance training. 

‚Äú20% of people have gym memberships. 50% of those people, use it. Now we are down to 10%. What percentage of them are doing resistance training‚Ä¶ maybe half.  So now we are down to 5% of people.‚Äù
- @michael_boyle1959 

We can debate plenty in our world today. One thing you can‚Äôt is that the number 1 avenue for lifespan and quality of life is resistance training. Our goal is always to have people leave feeling better than when they walked in.
transcript: Do we have a sense of what percentage of people in the United States do not practice resistance training? Well, we know that 50% of Americans are not training or doing any kind of exercise. I, from the research that I've read up until recently, um, it's probably 70% do not meet the criteria for both activities. 70% in total then? Or do you think it's 70% of people who are doing some form of exercise? Total. That's a great question. I believe that it is 70% of people in total. Got it. Okay. Is that I I can't even fact-check that, it's, I mean, that's hard for me to imagine, but I can believe it. I can believe it. I think it's lower, in terms of if you're talking about resistance training, 'cause we were talking. You would say lower than 30% would do resistance training then? Yeah, because I think 20% of people belong to a gym. If we look at home gym stats aren't very good in terms of people, they're the home gym person who actually has one and uses it is is probably more unicornie than we think they are. And so if you start looking at that number, 20% have a membership. 50% of those people use it, which now brings us down to only 10% of people in the United States are actually in a gym, and then you look at that and say what percentage of them are resistance training? Maybe now we're down to 5% because you see a lot more hamster wheel people who are just walking on a treadmill or walking on a stair climber or whatever it is. So, I would think the numbers are are pretty low. We spoke a little bit about this, but we have digital statistics that actually show people who have signed up to train with our programs, let's say, either be at home or at the gym, the percentage of people that make it through our programs is only 20%, and that's very high in terms of the industry standard. That's twice the industry standard for digital. Right. Which is usually like 10% or so. So, those are people who showed the commitment, made a purchase, put their hard-earned dollars behind it, have everything they need, I would think, in terms of the tools and sets and reps and what's supposed to be done, and only 10% will finish a program. So, I think that's that's a pretty uh, remarkable statement on what why why people can't. I think there's a lot more of a desire to to do things, but the the ability to actually follow through is where I think we're having the hardest time. So it might be then, Gabriel, your stat is 70% of 50, the reciprocal of that, 30% of 50, 15, it might be that our range is somewhere from 5 to 15% if I were going to sort of triangulate between these three data points. Again, that's that's kind of a hard thing to digest if you're asking the question, um, and and I've never been, um, sort of shy about my thesis, which is of all the pillars that we have, um, to embark on improving our health, whether it be changing our nutrition, improving our sleep, taking the medications and supplements that can be actually quite important, I don't I just don't see any evidence that anything trumps exercise, um, just purely from an actual lifespan perspective, and from the standpoint of reducing the risk of chronic disease. When you then layer in the benefits it has on quality of life, I mean, it's just sort of a no-brainer.

What % of the U.S. population engages in resistance training?

transcript: a question that probably has an answer. Although I actually am a bit embarrassed to say I don't know the answer. So, I'm wondering if one of you guys do. Do we have a sense of what percentage of people in the United States do not practice resistance training? I was listening recently to the excellent Peter Attia podcast, round table discussion on resistance training and Peter opened with this question and the uh, panel audience uh gave some mixed answers in terms of what the data shows. So, I wanted to dive in and clean some of that up. This data is the most recent I'm aware of from the CDC from 2020 that shows that approximately 31% of the US adult population engages in the recommended two times a week of muscle strengthening or resistance training activity. And it also shows that about half of the population just under, uh, engages in the recommended aerobic activity, which is about 180 minutes of moderate, brisk walking activity. If you look at those that meet both the uh physical activity guidelines for strength training and also for aerobic training then that shrinks down to about 24% just under a quarter of your adult US population is meeting the overall guidelines. I actually think this data from the CDC is a little more interesting from a longevity focus. This is looking at the percentage of the US adult population that meets those physical activity guidelines for strength training and aerobic training, but it buckets it both by sex and by age. And so you can see in the big green graphs there that over 40% of men 18 to 34 meet those physical activity guidelines and just under 30% of women uh, 18 to 34 meet those guidelines. But what you see in both men and women is this very sharp decline in meeting the physical activity guidelines by age. So to the point where they're 65 and older only 15% of men or 10% of women are meeting those guidelines. Or set another way, 85 to 90% of people that age are not meeting those physical activity guidelines.

Amazing Efforts 

1. Exercise Daily for at least an hour. You do not have to kill yourself from running, jogging, etc., but you should have some sort of moderate physical activity in your everyday life.

 2. Eat the Right Foods and Portion Each Meal
No matter how bad your stomach is telling you to go for candy over healthy food, try to stay away from sweets.

 3. Keep Track of Calories and Food Intake Per Day
Keeping track of how many calories you eat in a day will be helpful in planning out your physical exercising.

4. Be Sure to Get Sleep
Even though most of us have eight-hour jobs during the day or night, it is crucial to get enough sleep to recharge the body's batteries.

 5. Stay Motivated
An important key to being in shape is to set goals and keep a positive mindset. If you stay positive, you will be able to push yourself to get that fit body you've always wanted.

‚ú®üíñ Before I did ANYTHING, the first thing I had to do was  embrace this new journey of mommyhood‚ú®üíñ

üíñ Tip 1: Grant yourself grace ‚Äì celebrate small wins. In the whirlwind of new motherhood, it‚Äôs crucial to acknowledge and applaud your progress, no matter how small. 

‚ú®Example: Pat yourself on the back for consistent walks or completing a short workout; every effort is a victory.

üíñ Tip 2: Start with gentle walks, ease into weights. Your body underwent a miraculous journey, so introducing activity gradually is key. Begin with daily walks to boost energy and mood. As you feel ready, add lightweight exercises like bodyweight squats or resistance band workouts. 

‚ú® Example: Aim for 20 minutes of brisk walking three times a week, and add a simple bodyweight routine twice a week.

üíñ Tip 3: Nourish your body, and remember, self-care is non-negotiable. Prioritize nutrition to support your postpartum recovery. Include nutrient-dense foods like lean proteins, whole grains, and colorful veggies. Self-care isn‚Äôt selfish ‚Äì take a personal day to recharge, whether it‚Äôs a bubble bath, reading, or simply enjoying a quiet moment. 

‚ú® Example: Swap processed snacks for a balanced snack like Greek yogurt with berries, and schedule regular ‚Äòme time‚Äô for self-renewal.

Your well-being matters; keep shining, warrior! Remember, this is a never ending journey so grant yourself grace & take it day by day üåü #PostpartumFitness #WellnessJourney

‚ú® Understand this‚Ä¶ i workout for US! 

Because listen‚Ä¶ intrusive thoughts are real. And sometimes the only thing between me and a felony (misdemeanor already acquiredü´£) is a good lift, a loud playlist, and some deep breaths between sets.

I work out because it‚Äôs how I manage stress, keep my mind clear, and avoid making impulsive decisions that can really be life changing.

During workouts, my thoughts quiet down. I process things better. My mood lifts. And I walk out feeling in control of myself again.

üëâüèº Exercise has been proven to reduce cortisol (your stress hormone), improve decision-making, and help regulate emotional outbursts.
üëâüèº Lifting weights helps release endorphins, dopamine, and serotonin aka your brain‚Äôs NATURAL mood boosters.
üëâüèº And consistent movement literally rewires your brain over time to manage pressure better. (Neuro plasticity‚Ä¶ thank you @hubermanlab for teaching me neuroscience)

So if you‚Äôre stressed hit the gym‚Ä¶ Because jail is not fun. Nobody likes metal toilets, no seats, and zero privacy.
